<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The COI sequence is 4% divergent from the two specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sladen" baseAuthorityYear="1889" class="Crinoidea" family="Freyellidae" genus="Freyastera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Freyastera tuberculata" order="Forcipulatida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">Freyastera cf. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
reported herein, and hence considered a separate species. It is also divergent (&gt; 4% K2P distance) to sequences of other species of 
<taxonomicName class="Crinoidea" family="Freyellidae" genus="Freyastera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Freyastera" order="Forcipulatida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Freyastera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but forms a monophyletic clade with those, confirming its placement within the genus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 24" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figure 24. Rooted Bayesian phylogeny of Asteroidea. Concatenated (12 S, 16 S, 18 S, COI, and H 3) median consensus BEAST tree with posterior probability (PP) and bootstrap (BS) values indicated. Only values of PP&gt; 0.70 and BS&gt; 50 are shown, with values of PP&gt; 0.95 and BS&gt; 90 indicated with a circle. Nodes not recovered on the RAxML tree are indicated with a hyphen. Sequences generated in this study are highlighted in violet." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure24" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716350" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">24</figureCitation>
). Morphologically it resembles 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sladen" baseAuthorityYear="1889" class="Crinoidea" family="Freyellidae" genus="Freyastera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Freyastera tuberculata" order="Forcipulatida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">Freyastera cf. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
, but differ in having slightly shorter and more scattered spinelets on the abactinal surface of the disc. Also, the spinelets on the abactinal plates on the genital area are more numerous, and completely covered by a membrane bearing pedicellariae, instead of having a membrane that does not cover the spine all the way down to the base as in 
<taxonomicName genus="F." lsidName="F. tuberculata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tuberculata">F. cf. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
. In addition, the genetic distance with specimens of that species corresponds to the genetic distance between morphologically distinct species and hence considered a separate species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The specimen was collected on the sedimented abyssal plain of APEI 1 at 5204 m depth, with arms curled up like a basket (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 26" captionStartId="F26" captionText="Figure 26. Freyastera stet. CCZ _ 201 A in situ image B whole specimen C dorsal disc surface D ventral disc surface. Scale bars: 2 cm (A); 2 mm (B); 1 cm (C); 2 mm (D). Image attribution: Durden and Smith (A); Wiklund, Durden, Drennan, and McQuaid (B-D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1113.82172.figure26" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/716352" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">26A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comparisons">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comparison with image-based catalogue.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Crinoidea" family="Freyellidae" genus="Freyastera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Freyastera" order="Forcipulatida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Freyastera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. are commonly found in image-based megafauna assessments across the CCZ (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1038/srep30492" author="Amon, DJ" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Reports" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 12" refId="B4" refString="Amon, DJ, Ziegler, AF, Dahlgren, TG, Glover, AG, Goineau, A, Gooday, AJ, Wiklund, H, Smith, CR, 2016. Insights into the abundance and diversity of abyssal megafauna in a polymetallic-nodule region in the eastern Clarion-Clipperton Zone. Scientific Reports 6 (1): 1 - 12, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1038/srep30492" title="Insights into the abundance and diversity of abyssal megafauna in a polymetallic-nodule region in the eastern Clarion-Clipperton Zone." url="https://doi.org/10.1038/srep30492" volume="6" year="2016">Amon et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.5.e11794" author="Amon, DJ" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Reports" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B6" refString="Amon, DJ, Ziegler, AF, Kremenetskaia, A, Mah, CL, Mooi, R, O'Hara, T, Pawson, DL, Roux, M, Smith, CR, 2017b. Megafauna of the UKSRL exploration contract area and eastern Clarion-Clipperton Zone in the Pacific Ocean: Echinodermata. Biodiversity Data Journal 11794: e11794. https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.5.e11794" title="Megafauna of the UKSRL exploration contract area and eastern Clarion-Clipperton Zone in the Pacific Ocean: Echinodermata. Biodiversity Data Journal 11794: e 11794." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/BDJ.5.e11794" year="2017 b">Amon et al. 2017b</bibRefCitation>
), abyssal areas of the Kiribati EEZ, and other areas of the Pacific abyss (e.g., Peru Basin: 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-019-44492-w" author="Simon-Lledo, E" journalOrPublisher="Scientific Reports" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 13" refId="B84" refString="Simon-Lledo, E, Bett, BJ, Huvenne, VAI, Koser, K, Schoening, T, Greinert, J, Jones, DOB, 2019a. Biological effects 26 years after simulated deep-sea mining. Scientific Reports 9 (1): 1 - 13, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-019-44492-w" title="Biological effects 26 years after simulated deep-sea mining." url="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-019-44492-w" volume="9" year="2019 a">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Simon-Lledó">Simon-Lledo</normalizedToken>
et al. 2019a
</bibRefCitation>
), both in nodule fields and in seamount areas. The relatively large size of adult specimens facilitates the detection of these brisingids even upon imagery collected at high altitudes (&gt; 5 m) above the seabed. However, only one 
<taxonomicName class="Crinoidea" family="Freyellidae" genus="Freyastera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Freyastera" order="Forcipulatida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Freyastera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. morphotype (e.g., 
<taxonomicName class="Crinoidea" family="Freyellidae" genus="Freyastera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Freyastera" order="Forcipulatida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Freyastera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. indet., AST_002) has been catalogued so far, as differences in structure of the abactinal armament and/or the suboral spines are not visible from seabed images.
</paragraph>
